          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/974210-erik-graff?shelf=biography">biography</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer18426535" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9410803250806549338">With drugs, particularly pharmaceuticals, being so regularly abused in our culture, it is a salutary exercise to reconsider the sixties, when some psychoactive drugs, used considerately and independently of profit-driven corporations, turned millions towards the serious study of psychology, philosophy and religion. Richard Alpert and Timothy Leary were two prominent examples of this existential turn.<br/><br/>Of the two erstwhile Harvard academics, Alpert&apos;s is the happier story, Alpert the wiser man. This</span>
  <span id="freeText9410803250806549338" style="display:none">With drugs, particularly pharmaceuticals, being so regularly abused in our culture, it is a salutary exercise to reconsider the sixties, when some psychoactive drugs, used considerately and independently of profit-driven corporations, turned millions towards the serious study of psychology, philosophy and religion. Richard Alpert and Timothy Leary were two prominent examples of this existential turn.<br /><br />Of the two erstwhile Harvard academics, Alpert's is the happier story, Alpert the wiser man. This book, however, is Alpert at the turning point, Alpert telling the story of how L.S.D. turned him into the religious teacher, Baba Ram Dass.<br /><br />The story is quite fun to read, even hilarious. The whole book, and what Alpert ended up with, is a joy.<br /><br />I myself read this book in a study carrel on the second floor of the Grinnell College library.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9410803250806549338" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

