<span id="freeTextContainer4155902406903165928">I bought this book in 1972 (at age 11) to read in secret, then return to the bookstore some days later, for fear of discovery by my fundamentalist Christian father. I was seduced by the woodblock print on grocery-bag colored paper middle section. It left an indelible impression on me--one that would germinate 30 years later in my face-to-face encounter with Bhagavan Das, a much younger version of whom I first encountered in its pages.<br/>No other book has done more to support the healthy cross-polle</span>
  <span id="freeText4155902406903165928" style="display:none">I bought this book in 1972 (at age 11) to read in secret, then return to the bookstore some days later, for fear of discovery by my fundamentalist Christian father. I was seduced by the woodblock print on grocery-bag colored paper middle section. It left an indelible impression on me--one that would germinate 30 years later in my face-to-face encounter with Bhagavan Das, a much younger version of whom I first encountered in its pages.<br />No other book has done more to support the healthy cross-pollenation of East and West. It is the classic text of this genre.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4155902406903165928" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

