        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer509032482" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15528956401219305440">What a doozy of a book! I found it totally by accident. I had no idea it was by Alpert, or rather Baba Ram Dass, colleague of one Timothy Leary whose book Change Your Brain I&apos;d just read months earlier.<br/><br/>This is a one-of-a-kind &quot;trip.&quot; No, strip back those quotations marks, they dull the effect. This book IS a textual trip. I&apos;ve never seen another like it. Ram Dass writes a tasty and linear account of his transition from successful doctor Richard Alpert to spiritual explorer Ram Dass. The middle s</span>
  <span id="freeText15528956401219305440" style="display:none">What a doozy of a book! I found it totally by accident. I had no idea it was by Alpert, or rather Baba Ram Dass, colleague of one Timothy Leary whose book Change Your Brain I'd just read months earlier.<br /><br />This is a one-of-a-kind "trip." No, strip back those quotations marks, they dull the effect. This book IS a textual trip. I've never seen another like it. Ram Dass writes a tasty and linear account of his transition from successful doctor Richard Alpert to spiritual explorer Ram Dass. The middle section takes you out of your head--everything changes. The book turns, the text spins, but the ideas stay together in a way that, in my case at least, really did seem to dig under the rational part of me and yank up the good stuff; the Atman; the everlasting onion bulb.<br /><br />If you're at all interested in exploration of self, this is probably a necessity. I'm so glad I found it by accident, and so disappointed I have to return it. I imagine I'll buy it someday. It's better than any Bible, IMHO.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15528956401219305440" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


